descript.abstract: U.S. Populated Place Points represents populated places that include census designated places, consolidated cities, and incorporated places within United States identified by the U.S. Bureau of the Census.
descript.purpose: U.S. Populated Place Points provides locations for populated places including attributes - name, FIPS code, Census class, area, and selected demographic data.
descript.supplinf: Largest scale when displaying the data: 1:250,000. This is an ESRI dataset that was reprojected to UTM NAD 83 Zone 15N by Iowa DNR.

enttyp.enttypd: The points represent concentrations of population that include census designated places, consolidated cities, and incorporated places identified by the U.S. Census Bureau.

attrdomv.udom: Sequential unique whole numbers that are automatically generated.

attr.attrdef: The class of the populated place.

edom.edomvd: In Connecticut, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania, an incorporated place.

Census designated place - A statistical entity, defined for each decennial census according to Census Bureau guidelines, comprising a densely settled concentration of population that is not within an incorporated place, but is locally identified by a name.

An incorporated place in 49 States and the District of Columbia. In 20 States, some or all cities are not part of any minor civil division, and the Census Bureau also treats these as county subdivisions, statistically equivalent to minor civil divisions.
The portion of the consolidated city minus the incorporated places. For statistical purposes, these entities are treated as statistically equivalent to a place and have no legal basis or functions.
An incorporated place in 30 States. In New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and South Dakota, the Census Bureau treats these towns as the equivalent of a minor civil division.
An incorporated place in 20 States. The Census Bureau treats all villages in New Jersey, South Dakota, and Wisconsin, and some villages in Ohio as county subdivisions.

overview.eaover: Iowa DNR added the LEGEND field to the attribute table. The LEGEND field describes the population of the place. This column is used in ArcSDE spatial views for including or not including specific cities, depending on population size. A value of 4 is a city with population >= 100K, 3 is a city with population >= 30K, 2 is a city with population >= 5K, and a value of 1 is a place with a population < 5K. Iowa DNR also added the LABEL field, so that labelling could be done on the unique highway types in the LEGEND column. The LABEL field contains the interstate or highway number only and not the full name, and is meant to be used as the field for labelling road features.

digtinfo.formspec: The SHP file contains the geospatial data. The SHX file contains the index of the geospatial data. The DBF file contains the attribute data in dBASE format. The PRJ file contains the coordinate system information (optional). The AVL file contains the legend information (optional). The SBN and SBX files contain the spatial index of the geospatial data (optional). The XML file contains the metadata describing the data set <data set name>.shp.xml (optional).

citeinfo.title: Summary File 1 (SF1)
citeinfo.othercit: The Summary File 1 (SF1) data is based on the 2000 Census of Population. The geospatial data is calculated from the latitude/longitude coordinate attributes.

procstep.procdesc:
The following steps were performed by ESRI for Data & Maps 2002: Created a data set by extracting populated places from U.S. Bureau of the Census 2000 Summary File 1 (SF1). Ran ArcView command Add Event Theme on the data set to create the point location centroids shapefile. Reformatted attributes and finalized attribute order. Created ArcView legend file (.avl), ArcGIS™ layer file (.lyr) file, projection file (.prj), and spatial indices.
This is an ESRI dataset that was reprojected to UTM NAD 83 Zone 15N by Iowa DNR.

horizpa.horizpar: The geospatial part of this data set was calculated from latitude/longitude coordinates from the U.S. Bureau of the Census 2000 Summary File 1 (SF1). The horizontal positional accuracy is unknown.
